One of the more interesting problems in options trading is forecasting how implied volatility (IV) 
will evolve over the remaining life of a contract. If you can do this, you can identify 
mispricings in the options market and trade against them systematically.

Before getting into the details, I want to note that some of the context required to fully 
appreciate what is going on here, particularly around how the contracts are selected and how the 
ARIMA step works, will have to come in later posts. That said, I am going to try to give as much useful 
detail as I can here so that the overall picture is at least clear. And it goes without saying that
some important details I can't share due to the proprietary nature of the work involved.

The naive approach is to fit a time series model directly to the IV of each contract and forecast 
forward. The problem is that IV series are noisy, non-stationary in complicated ways, and each 
contract has its own dynamics depending on its strike, tenor, and the underlying's behavior at that 
point in time. A single model fit across everything tends to perform poorly.

The approach I took instead is a hybrid: use ARIMA to capture the smooth, mean-reverting component 
of each contract's IV trajectory, and then train a separate XGBoost model to predict the residuals 
that ARIMA gets wrong. The final forecast is just the sum of the two:

\\[\hat{y} = \hat{y}_{\text{ARIMA}} + \hat{r}_{\text{XGBoost}}\\]

The idea is that ARIMA handles the trend and autocorrelation structure reasonably well, but it has 
no way to incorporate cross-sectional information like IV skew, tenor, or the day of the week. 
XGBoost can learn those patterns from the residuals across all contracts simultaneously, which is 
where the leverage comes from.

The ARIMA(p, d, q) model expresses the differenced series as a linear combination of its own past 
values and past forecast errors:

\\[\Delta^d y_t = c + \sum_{i=1}^{p} \phi_i \Delta^d y_{t-i} + \sum_{j=1}^{q} \theta_j \varepsilon_{t-j} + \varepsilon_t\\]

where \\(\phi_i\\) are the autoregressive coefficients, \\(\theta_j\\) are the moving average 
coefficients, \\(d\\) is the order of differencing, and \\(\varepsilon_t\\) is white noise. The 
orders \\(p\\), \\(d\\), and \\(q\\) are selected separately per contract by minimizing an 
information criterion.

The pipeline works as follows. For each options contract, I split the observed IV history into a 
fit window and a validation window. ARIMA is fit on the fit window, and its out-of-sample forecasts 
over the validation window give both a predicted trajectory and confidence intervals. The 
difference between those forecasts and the actual observed IV is the residual:

\\[r_t = y_t - \hat{y}_{\text{ARIMA}, t}\\]

and that residual becomes the target for XGBoost.

The features I pass to XGBoost are things that are available at inference time. The 
lagged residuals are important because ARIMA residuals tend to be autocorrelated in ways that 
ARIMA itself does not fully capture, and XGBoost can exploit that structure.

One subtlety worth mentioning is that the lag features have to be computed per contract before 
concatenating everything into a single training dataset. If you compute them after concatenation, 
lags will bleed across contract boundaries and you will be leaking information from one contract 
into another.

After training, the model is applied at inference time to the forward window of each contract: 
from the last observed point out to expiry. The ARIMA forward forecast gives the baseline 
trajectory, XGBoost predicts the residual correction at each timestep, and the sum gives the 
final IV forecast. I also compute the probability that realized IV will fall below the forecast 
at each point. Using the ARIMA confidence interval as a proxy for the distribution, and treating 
the interval as approximately normal, the standard deviation at each timestep is:

\\[\sigma_t = \frac{\text{upper}_t - \text{lower}_t}{2 \times 1.96}\\]

which gives the probability that realized IV falls below the hybrid forecast as:

\\[P(\text{IV} \leq \hat{y}_t) = \Phi\left(\frac{\hat{y}_t - \hat{y}_{\text{ARIMA}, t}}{\sigma_t}\right)\\]

where \\(\Phi\\) is the standard normal CDF. This gives a sense of where in the ARIMA confidence 
interval the hybrid forecast is landing, which turns out to be a useful signal on its own.

There is a lot more to say about the ARIMA fitting procedure, how contracts are selected, and how 
the forecasts are actually used to construct trades. I will get into those in future posts.
